06111nam a22007215i 9780822393221DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223932217 a10.1515/97808223932212doi  a(DE-B1597)551747  a(OCoLC)1097094795  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a30100aIn the Name of Humanity :bThe Government of Threat and Care /ced. by Ilana Feldman, Miriam Ticktin. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (389 p.) :b10 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Government and Humanity -- tWhen Humanity Sits in Judgment Crimes against Humanity and the Conundrum of Race and Ethnicity at the International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda -- tChildren, Humanity, and the Infantilization of Peace -- tNarrative, Humanity, and Patrimony in an Equatorial African Forest -- tInhumanitas Political Speciation, Animality, Natality, Defacement -- t“Medication is me now” Human Values and Political Life in the Wake of Global aids Treatment -- tEnvironment, Community, Government -- tThe Mortality Effect. Counting the Dead in the Cancer Trial -- tInequality of Lives, Hierarchies of Humanity. Moral Commitments and Ethical Dilemmas of Humanitarianism -- tThe Politics of Experimentality -- tStealth Nature. Biomimesis and the Weaponization of Life -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aScientists, activists, state officials, NGOs, and others increasingly claim to speak and act on behalf of “humanity.” The remarkable array of circumstances in which humanity is invoked testifies to the category’s universal purchase. Yet what exactly does it mean to govern, fight, and care in the name of humanity? In this timely collection, leading anthropologists and cultural critics grapple with that question, examining configurations of humanity in relation to biotechnologies, the natural environment, and humanitarianism and human rights. From the global pharmaceutical industry, to forest conservation, to international criminal tribunals, the domains they analyze highlight the diversity of spaces and scales at which humanity is articulated.The editors argue that ideas about humanity find concrete expression in the governing work that operationalizes those ideas to produce order, prosperity, and security. As a site of governance, humanity appears as both an object of care and a source of anxiety. Assertions that humanity is being threatened, whether by environmental catastrophe or political upheaval, provide a justification for the elaboration of new governing techniques. At the same time, humanity itself is identified as a threat (to nature, to nation, to global peace) which governance must contain. These apparently contradictory understandings of the relation of threat to the category of humanity coexist and remain in tension, helping to maintain the dynamic co-production of governance and humanity.Contributors. Arun Agrawal, Joao Biehl , Didier Fassin, Allen Feldman, Ilana Feldman, Rebecca Hardin, S. Lochann Jain, Liisa Malkki, Adriana Petryna, Miriam Ticktin, Richard Ashby Wilson, Charles Zerner  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHumanity. 0aPolitical ethics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAgrawal, Arun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiehl, João, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFassin, Didier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Allen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, 